column11: U.S. retail sales have had dramatic swings during the COVID-19 pandemic, placing the fate of retailers' all-important holiday season in flux (Business Wire, CNBC). The outcome will be determined using seasonally adjusted "Retail Trade and Food Services, ex Auto and Gas" data from the U.S. Census Bureau for November and December 2020 relative to the same period in 2019, expected to be released in January 2021 (Census.gov). To retrieve the data go to https://www.census.gov/retail/index.html and under the "Advance Monthly Retail Trade Report" section, select "Time Series/Trend Charts: Create your own customizable time series." Do the following in each of the five options: (1) select "Advanced Monthly Sales for Retail and Food Services," (2) set Start at 2019 and End at 2020, (3) select "44W72: Retail Trade and Food Services, ex Auto and Gas," (4) select "Sales - Monthly," and (5) select "U.S. Total" and check off only "Seasonally Adjusted." For November and December 2019, the Bureau reported combined sales of 754,030 [millions of dollars].

-15 on over 5%. I see links in the comments about a number around 3% for this season, but that looks like it's based on a MasterCard spending pulse analysis, and looking at the previous years I don't see much correlation between the MasterCard spending pulse year over year holiday growth and the Census data holiday growth. That said, in case I'm looking at the data incorrectly or missing something I'm coming down a bit on over 5%, though I still think it's more likely. There would have to be a pretty big decline from November 2020 to December 2020 to drop it under 5%, and an impossibly large decline to go below 2.5%.

Based on the November release, this question can still resolve with >5% if month over month sales in Dec fall by less than 1.3%. For the question to resolve in the 2.5-5% bucket, sales must fall between 1.3-6%. Neither is not unreasonable (they fell by 2.4% from Feb to Mar this year and 14% from Mar to Apr). On the other hand, sales fell by only 0.8% in Nov and <0.1% in Oct.

Latest release just dropped, November 2020 is up 5.93% over November 2019. Looking at the November to December change December usually is very close to November. The biggest change since 2005 was in 2018 when December was down 2.56% from November. So looking at some rough numbers, if December is around where November is at it would be more than a 5% increase from December 2019. If it dropped like it did in 2018 December would still be a 3% gain over December 2019. Based on that I'm -10 on the 0 to 2.5% category and +55 on higher by more than 5%.

There has only been 1 year since 2002 that has seen a year over year decrease in holiday spending and that was 2008. Obviously, the economic situation is closer to the situation in 2008 than it was in 2019, which saw a strong economy. However, consumer spending since April has soared past even pre-pandemic levels, which indicates consumers are willing to spend and have the resources to do so. It will not be an earth-shattering increase but i would expect about a 2 percent bump, still below average, in spending for the holidays.
